  1. Use the adjacency matrix created above and convert it to a network object using igraph package. Plot the network showing all the node labels. (10 points)
V(egraph)$size <- 25
simplify(egraph) %>% plot(edge.arrow.size=.4, edge.curved=.1)

  1. Add a node (vertex) attribute and name it as type. Assign value A to nodes S01 to s08, value B to nodes S09 to s14, and value C to nodes S15 to s17. Plot the network showing all node labels and color node by type attribute. (10 points)
V(egraph)$type[V(egraph)$name %in% c("s01","s02","s03","s04","s05","s06","s07","s08")] <- "A"
V(egraph)$type[V(egraph)$name %in% c("s09","s10","s11","s12","s13","s14")] <- "B"
V(egraph)$type[V(egraph)$name %in% c("s15","s16","s17")] <- "C"
col <- c("gray50", "tomato", "gold")
V(egraph)$color <- col[factor(V(egraph)$type) %>% as.numeric()]
simplify(egraph) %>% plot(edge.arrow.size=.4, edge.curved=.1)
  1. Plot the network showing all nodes such that the node sizes are varied according their respective degrees. (10 points)
deg <- degree(egraph,mode="all")
V(egraph)$size <- deg*3
V(egraph)$color <- "white"
simplify(egraph) %>% plot(edge.arrow.size=.4, edge.curved=.1)
